  "text": "Atrous convolution has a long history in the filed of signal processing. It is initially created for efficient computation of undecimated wavelet transform in the \"algorithmeà trous\" scheme [CITATION_1] . Atrous convolution is a term that was firstly used in [CITATION_2] and introduced into semantic segmentation in DeepLab [10]. The same operation was later called dilated convolution (motivated by the fact that such an operation corresponds to the standard convolution with a dilated filter) in [CITATION_3] . The idea of atrous convolution is to convolve the input image with the upsampling filter produced by inserting zeros (or holes) between each pair of consecutive non-zero filter values. Compared with the standard convolution, atrous convolution can effectively increase the size of receptive fields and generate denser feature maps without increasing the amount of computation and the number of parameters.",
